Approach B:
- Describe: Take a single snapshot once per batch (after processing all records), reducing snapshot frequency.
- What would change?: Instead of N snapshots for N records, there will be 1 snapshot per batch. This reduces cost but changes snapshot semantics.
- What could break?: Any downstream consumer that expects per-record snapshots (e.g., verify_consistency which expects snapshots per processed record) will break. Reports and consistency checks relying on per-record snapshots will be invalid.

Evaluation:
- Which preserves all existing behavior?: Approach A preserves existing behavior for callers that use process_batch (it still results in one snapshot per record). It does not change the number/timing of snapshots when batches are processed via process_batch. Approach B does not preserve behavior because it reduces snapshots to one per batch.
- Which risks breaking downstream consumers?: Approach B is riskier, since many consumers may depend on per-record snapshots. Approach A only risks callers that call process_record directly.

Safer approach: Approach A. It centralizes snapshotting at the batch level while preserving existing per-record snapshot semantics for process_batch-based ingestion. The only risk is direct callers of process_record losing snapshot side-effects.

