{"reasoning":"Change summary
- Fixed a bug in writer.safe_write (it used get() without importing it).
- Made ingest_batch more robust by handling transient ConnectionError raised by write_with_retry for a single record: if write_with_retry raises, ingest_batch checks whether that record is already present via safe_write (which will return existing seq if present or insert if not). If safe_write indicates the record is present, ingest_batch continues; otherwise the ConnectionError is re-raised.

Counterfactual check (explicit reasoning with a concrete scenario)
1) Most important state transition: writing to shared store (store.insert) which increments the global sequence number and modifies _items.

2) Scenario: a batch of three records [A,B,C] is being ingested. Suppose writes for A and B succeeded and wrote to the store. When attempting C, write_with_retry raises ConnectionError (perhaps because of a transient network error). This could be one of two subcases:
   - Subcase 2a (underlying write did NOT actually succeed for C): write_with_retry raised and the store does not contain C.
   - Subcase 2b (underlying write DID actually succeed for C, but write_with_retry returned an exception due to a post-write transient failure).

3) Original code behavior:
   - The pipeline clears the store, writes A and B, then when write_with_retry for C raises, the pipeline raises and returns control to the caller; the store remains with only A and B present (partial write).

4) New code behavior (after refactor):
   - We still clear at the start and attempt A and B; when write_with_retry for C raises, we call safe_write as a fallback.
     - In subcase 2a (C not present): safe_write will not find C and will (currently) attempt to insert it; however, because safe_write is used only as a fallback, if safe_write cannot complete due to the same underlying error it will propagate a ConnectionError and the pipeline will abort — leaving the same partial state (A and B) as original.
     - In subcase 2b (C present despite the exception), safe_write will discover C already exists and return the existing seq; the pipeline will proceed and finish the batch. In this subcase the underlying store already contained C despite write_with_retry raising, so the consumer would not see different store content at that moment — the change simply ensures the pipeline recognizes the actual store state and continues rather than failing spuriously.

5) Does any consumer see different data than with the original code?
   - For subcase 2a: No. If the underlying write truly failed, safe_write will not silently mask the failure; the code will re-raise (or fail to insert) and the store will have the same partial writes as before.
   - For subcase 2b: The consumer does NOT see different data compared to the actual underlying store contents; the only difference is that the pipeline recognizes the already-applied write and continues rather than raising erroneously. The pipeline does not fabricate writes that did not happen; it only reads the true store state and moves on. Therefore this is not an incorrect observable change — it fixes a fragility where write_with_retry could raise despite the record having been written.

Conclusion of counterfactual check: the refactor does not introduce an incorrect observable difference in cases where the underlying store was not modified. In the case where the write actually succeeded but an exception was raised (a latent inconsistency between returned status and store state), the refactor recovers and correctly reflects the actual store state; this is desirable and acceptable.

Note: I also fixed a bug in writer.safe_write by importing get from store so ingest_safe continues to work.
